 false, "mention": "thrombosis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999839067459106, "span": {"begin": 552, "end": 562}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000347"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Hypofibrinolysis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999938011169434, "span": {"begin": 593, "end": 609}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5054"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "PAI-1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9895602464675903, "span": {"begin": 672, "end": 677}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:118471"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "uPA", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9970628619194031, "span": {"begin": 694, "end": 697}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5329"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "uPAR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.992571234703064, "span": {"begin": 698, "end": 702}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1401"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CRP", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9910955429077148, "span": {"begin": 730, "end": 733}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000347"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "hypofibrinolysis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9994654059410095, "span": {"begin": 752, "end": 768}}, {"id": ["CL:0000115"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "endothelial cell", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.6057566404342651, "span": {"begin": 812, "end": 828}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009410"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "endothelial cell dysfunction", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9175519943237305, "span": {"begin": 812, "end": 840}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3558"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9199256896972656, "span": {"begin": 925, "end": 929}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7124"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TNF", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9572886824607849, "span": {"begin": 931, "end": 934}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3569"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-6", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9860104322433472, "span": {"begin": 940, "end": 944}}], "text": "Hypofibrinolysis is the process of a decreased fibrinolytic response, or decreasing the breakdown of fibrin in blood clots.&nbsp; Hallmarks of a hypofibrinolysis state include elevated levels of TAFI and PAI-1 inhibitors, a dysregulated uPA/uPAR system, increased fibrinogen, and high levels of CRP (Bachler et al, 2021). These markers were found as a result of perturbation from SARS-COV-2 infection, although nanomaterial stressors can result in hypofibrinolysis as well. The results of hypofibrinolysis include an increase in coagulation levels and thrombosis(Hofman et al, 2016).  &nbsp;  Hypofibrinolysis increases proinflammatory mediator levels through increase in PAI-1, a dysregulated uPA/uPAR system, and high levels of CRP. These markers of hypofibrinolysis increase proinflammatory mediators through endothelial cell dysfunction and activate pathways that lead to an increase in proinflammatory cytokines such as IL-2, TNF, and IL-6.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:33:45 +0000 2026"}